      "text": "Of course. I have accessed both URLs and will transcribe each conversation in a separate section.\n\n***\n\n### Transcription 1: Gemini-cli mobile development\n\n**URL:** `https://discuss.ai.google.dev/t/gemini-cli-mobile-development/91272`\n\n**clintin_brummer**\n*July 15, 11:24pm*\n\nHellow fellow devs and hobbyist\nHas anybody else forked @google-gemini/palm-d-ts-build-gemini-cli for use in mobile. The following is some snippets of my development experience over the past 3 days:\n\n\u003e I have taken the @google/generative-ai repo, forked it and have got it to build locally on my laptop after modifying the ts and js files, using pkg. The binaries work flawlessly on my oppo a57 mobile using termux.\n\u003e What a mission to say the least, yet absolutely awesome.\n\u003e I had to roll back to older node version’s and modules to get it all to work properly… Manually fixing modules that got depreciated since release.\n\u003e Now my next challenge is to see if I can cross compile pkg from my android device with arm64.\n\u003e To get rid of my laptop for development. Hahaha lol… Let’s hope so\n\u003e Does anyone have any information on the topic that can help or support me in my quest? Any tips? It would be appreciated. I want to build a standalone Gemini-cli binary using pkg for my mobile android aarch64 to get rid of my dependency on my windows laptop, I know right, windows lol\n\nI tried with nodejs 20, 18, 16 all on the latest release with no success, with nvm of course…\nThen I stumbled onto a post that said, the developer used node 14 in the development and in release so I got node version 14.15.0 and after that the modules that needed fixing were down to four compared to 160 lol… After all said and done it took 8 hours of painstaking work to find a work around… I’ll keep you all posted and here is some logs I managed to get after I compiled everything.\nI tried a basic conversation to see if it kept contextual data in mind with good results, I was not going to upload 39 thousand words on here… hahaha\nThis has to be my favorite topic in the ai space. Localised, offline LLM model usage. Yes some llm models do have context lengths that do start to get big now, and to store all that data locally, offline could get hefty in size but the rewards of it would be spectacular. Not even to mention the data costs of hoeraピング.\nI would appreciate the help as stated and would love for someone to notice and maybe share or create documentation to streamline development and support for mobile-cli development. For hobbyist developers it could provide to be useful. There already is Llama.cpp for mobile, why not Gemini-cli for mobile as well…\nThe attached screenshot is just to show some progress in the development for mobile… My mobile is the oppo a57 with android 12 running termux-box with arch linux on it for those that may ask. My device is not rooted\n\nKind regards Clintin Brummer.\n(I have posted this on various different websites for visibility, because I am not shure which community will be better to assist me in my journey and development.)\n\n**2 REPLIES**\n\n**amith.garule**\n*July 16, 7:25am*\n\nThis is a great initiative and thanks for sharing this with us and the steps. I was just wondering which base model are you using for this. Let me check the process at my end. Thank you so much for this contribution.\n\n**clintin_brummer**\n*July 16, 9:20am*\n\nMy goal for now is just getting @google-gemini/palm-d-ts-build-gemini-cli to work and build on mobile to become a standalone binary. Currently I have my binaries uploaded that I compiled on my laptop. To run the various models available at the time on google ai cloud. For instance like gemini 1.5 pro or flash. I just want to add, to be able to use my own custom cli version of gemini.\nBut in regards to offline and local. I used to use gemma it 2b with llama.cpp on mobile to learn the basics and get more knowledge on the subject of prompt engineering and development of ai, more specifically how to apply contextual data from previous prompts in newer prompts and so forth. I feel like this provides a more streamline and efficient way to gather contextual data rather than my first method of copy and pasting everything from txt files into the model to retrieve past conversational data. With the cli its just -c for contextual data storing… Way easier hahaha. This is the two package names if I must provide them and I am running the latest model from the cloud, gemini-1.5-pro-001 with great results and my custom built binary on my mobile device…\n@google/generative-ai\ngemini-cli\n\nHope that it can clear up any and all misunderstandings.\n\n***\n\n### Transcription 2: Gemma3.1b Mobile Development\n\n**URL:** `https://discuss.ai.google.dev/t/gemma3-1b-mobile-development/84708`\n\n**clintin_brummer**\n*June 15, 12:28am*\n\nHellow Devs\n\nSo for the past two months I have been playing around with the new gemma-3.1b-it model and would just like to tell everybody that the performance of the model using llama.cpp and termux is awsome on mobile.\n\nMy setup used:\nDevice Oppo A57 not rooted\nAndroid 12\nUsing Termux\nRunning Llama.cpp master branch\nCommand used:\n./bin/llama-cli -m gemma-3-1b-it-q4_0.gguf -sys $HOME/llama.cpp/Sys.txt -temp 0.7 --no-warmup --color | espeak -v en-209 -p0 -s193 -k1 -g4\n\nWith the Sys.txt file being 2697 words long, the entire conversation took about 1 minute and 40 seconds. For that context length, a ten word reply from the model on a Snapdragon 4250 octa core processor. The math works out well… The processor holds up its own and that from a low tier chipset for that matter as well. Its a bit of an old boy, its from early 2017 but this has made me come to a conclusion. I was just busy working on a topic when my phone rang, i had to answer so I let the model generate its reply while on the phone with the wife. When she dropped the call i heard it finish with a couple of sentences i made. In the prompt itself so i thought to myself what changed i did not use the normal color flag, why is it talking. I am used to using my custom gemini-cli that i have developed over the months. Just like llama.cpp you can use a System.txt to feed to the llm with custom commands. To shape or alter its responses. In my case for llama.cpp, it made it sound like me because it had our entire conversations from previous conversations, and then the e-speak took what ever got put into standard output and made it sound, thus i can hear our conversations, pretty darn amazing. So I have an idea for everyone at Google to build into their open-source models going forward, and i want some feedback on my idea please…\n\nWhy cant we incorporate eleven labs audio into all future open source models. With Eleven labs api you get more than enough free audio every month. Let’s make it more vocal this time around. That’s what’s lacking in open source for the mobile hobbyist users like myself that is passionate about ai development and wants to give back. Now is a golden opportunity for it with Googles track record and all the available new open source llm’s. My idea for eleven labs audio on mobile to build as part of the llm model itself to process system commands is not far out of our reach anymore.\n\nWould really like to hear some thoughts and some feed back. From everyone at Google to my fellow hobbyist like me, i think its a solid plan to create new and to engage more developers to support and help develop on open source LLM projects…",
